[The information on the detection of ASF virus in pork products introduced from Macau, a territory so far not named to be ASF-infected, should not surprise. The disease has been recently reported from a slaughterhouse in Zhuhai, Guangdong province (20181219.6216012). Zhuhai is a modern city in China's southern Guangdong province, just on the border with Macau; map at https://tinyurl.com/ycud2jg5.

Earlier, infected pork products from China were also intercepted in South Korea, Japan, and Thailand. Customs, regulatory and quarantine services worldwide, should be equipped to effectively intercept illegal/unregulated foodstuffs and other hazardous materials at international airports, seaports, and border crossings. Confiscated materials should be destroyed or disposed of safely and not dumped within reach of scavengers (animals and humans). Past events suggest that particular attention should be paid to the proper disposal of waste food from aircraft, ships, or vehicles from infected countries, preferably by incineration or, if available, by rendering.

In the meantime, China has stiffened its own measures to prevent human-borne spread of the virus. A recent media report informed the arrest of a man suspected of illegally feeding the pigs on his farm unsterilized kitchen waste sourced from other provinces, leading to an outbreak of ASF in Shanghai; see https://www.shine.cn/news/metro/1812227104 (thanks to Kunihiko Iizuka for the submission). - Mod.AS

